description: Australian biosecurity officers begin screening arrivals from Wuhan in Sydney.
Authorities confirm that three cases in Sydney and one in Melbourne are the first cases of COVID-19 in Australia. Government advises “do not travel” to Hubei province, China.
Hundreds of Australians are evacuated from Wuhan in a repatriation flight. Travellers from China are barred from entering Australia.
Prime Minister Scott Morrison announces activation of an emergency plan in response to COVID-19, extends travel ban from China. 14-day isolation required for returning Australians.
A man from Perth is the first person in Australian to die as a result of COVID-19.
Sydney has Australia’s first two cases of COVID-19 community transmission.
Sydney’s first COVID-19 death is a woman from an aged care facility. Supermarket panic buying begins.
The Prime Minister announces $17.6 billion stimulus package to protect the economy from the effects of coronavirus.
The New South Wales Health Minister implements a ban on events of more than 500 people.
The New South Wales Government announces a $2.3 billion health and economic stimulus package.

Prime Minister announces a ban on indoor events of more than 100 people and prohibits international travel. Social distancing of 1.5 metres is encouraged. The Govenor-General declares a biosecurity emergency.

Passengers disembark from the Ruby Princess cruise ship in Sydney, despite many being sick with COVID-19. This error by health authorities was later determined to have caused the spread of 662 coronavirus cases and death of 28.
Australian borders close to all non-residents.

Australia enters stage one lockdown, with all hospitality allowed to offer takeaway only, and shops subject to social distancing guidelines. Non-essential travel is prohibited. NSW Premier encourages parents to keep children home from school. $66 billion in business financial support announced.
Stage two lockdown in force, with further restrictions on indoor activities, gyms, weddings and funerals.
Hotel quarantine program begins, enforcing a two-week stay in a hotel for all new arrivals into Australia.
New South Wales bans gatherings of more than two people. Citizens told to cancel plans to travel to regional areas for Easter.
NSW Premier announces a phased return to school, from mid-May, for all children who had so far been kept home.
Federal government releases the COVIDSafe app which aims to identify possible exposure to COVID-19.
Up to two adults are now allowed to visit another household in New South Wales.
NSW Minister for Health Brad Hazzard announces property inspections and on-site auctions may resume.
Prime Minister announces three-step plan “Roadmap to COVIDSafe Australia” for easing coronavirus restrictions, to be implemented by each state independently.

NSW’s restrictions ease in line with the federal government roadmap’s first step, including: outdoor gatherings allowed up to 10 people, up to five household visitors allowed, and hospitality venues able to serve ten patrons at a time.

Further easing of restrictions in NSW, with hospitality venues allowed to serve 50 people, libraries and museums reopened, travel to regional NSW allowed and up to 50 people allowed to attend church services. More public transport services provided to aid physical distancing.
Gyms and recreational facilities allowed to reopen in NSW, with venue limits.
Kids' sport and community sport resumes in NSW. Capacity increases on public transport.
NSW Health places a cap of 450 on daily arrivals at Sydney Airport to ease pressure on hotel quarantine.
Off-peak discount of 50% introduced on public transport services in Sydney to incentivise staggered travel and aid social distancing.

Restrictions introduced for hospitality venues, with a maximum of 10 at a table and a cap of 300 in a venue at any one time. COVID safe hygiene Marshalls will enforce restrictions with a COVID Safe plan.
Restrictions added to limit the size of weddings and corporate events to 150 people; with funerals and worship capped at 100 people.
Low case numbers prompt easing of restrictions in a school environment, including community sports, camps, music and high school formals allowed.
Cinemas and concert venues allowed to increase capacity up to 50%, corporate events cap raised to 300 people.
NSW Government announces pilot of outdoor dining in Sydney to encourage patronage of hospitality venues after covid.

Trans-Tasman travel bubble begins with New Zealand travellers able to enter Australia without a quarantine period. Capacity doubles in hospitality venues, with one person per two square metres instead of four.

Number of people able to gather outdoors increased from 20 to 30, and number at a table in hospitality venues raised from 10 to 30. Limits on gym operation and religious worship ceremonies also eased.
NSW Government announces “Out and About” scheme to stimulate local dining and entertainment by giving citizens digital vouchers. The scheme is to launch in January 2021.
Recording customer information digitally becomes law in NSW, with the Service NSW app available since September.
Capacity increases on Public Transport across NSW.
A COVID-19 hotspot is declared in Sydney’s northern beaches, prompting the government to instruct residents of the area to work from home and avoid unnecessary gatherings.

Premier Gladys Berejiklian imposes lockdown restrictions across Sydney including a limit of 10 visitors to homes and the reintroduction for hospitality of the rule of one patron per 4 square metres. Residents of the Northern Beaches are not allowed to leave their area. The use of face masks is encouraged.
Sydneysiders limited to gatherings of five indoors and 30 outdoors to celebrate the New Year amid the northern beaches outbreak.
Wearing of face masks becomes compulsory when in certain areas in NSW. Capacity of gyms, worship, weddings, funerals and performance venues are reduced.
Restrictions eased as case numbers drop, with masks no longer compulsory. The Premier waits a further two weeks before easing hospitality density limits.
First COVID-19 Vaccine administered in Australia, to a Sydney aged care resident.
Cross-Tasman travel bubble now allows no-quarantine flights between Australia and New Zealand in either direction
After another outbreak in Sydney, restrictions are tightened for four days, with face masks again compulsory and a reduction in social gathering limits.
Restrictions extended until 17 May as missing links in chain of transmission are still not identified.
Restrictions introduced on May 6 are removed.
